de.rincewind.api.gui.elements

Interface ElementList<T>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - specifying the object-type
    All Superinterfaces:
    Element, ElementDisplayable, ElementSizeable, EventBased, java.lang.Iterable<ElementList.ListItem<T>>, Selectable, Sizeable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    CraftElementList, Elements.ElementListExtendable

    public interface ElementList<T>
extends ElementSizeable, java.lang.Iterable<ElementList.ListItem<T>>, Selectable
    With this element you can create a list of entries and you are able to scroll through the entries. The list can be resized, and perhaps the entries will be resized too. You can only scroll in one direction through the list. This depends on the type of this list. If the type is Directionality.HORIZONTAL the entries will be rendered laying from the right to the left (Horizontal), so they will be added to the list from the top to the bottom. With Directionality.VERTICAL the same but you scroll the right to the left. This element contains its own color. This color will be displayed, when there are not enough entries to fill the area of the list, or when you scroll to the end of the list. If the user clicks on an entry, this entry will be selected (by the default, it will be enchanted). By an second click on the selected entry, the entry will be unselected. For a better handling with this element, you can 'save' an object from an specified type in each list-entry. You can get this object from each entry. For example you can save a String in an entry an your able to identify the entries by that string. Therefore, you do not have to compare the icons or the entries its self. This element implements Iterable to iterate throw all added entries. This element implements Selectable and defines the method Selectable.select() as this.select(0) with a little check if the size is not 0. If it is 0 the APIException will be thrown. The ListSelectEvent will be called, when the user selects an entry or you calls the method select(int). The ListUnselectEvent will be called, when the user unselects the selected entry or you calls the method Selectable.unselect().
    Since:
    2.3.3
    Author:
    Rincewind34

      • addScroler

        void addScroler(ElementButton btn,
                int value)
        Adds to an ElementButton a listener to scroll through this element. The value to scroll forwards by clicking the button can be specified. If the user shiftclicks the button, the value will be multiplied by 2. You can also set the value to a number smaller than 0 to scroll backwards through this element by clicking the button.
        Parameters:

        value - scrolling through this element by clicking

        java.lang.NullPointerException - if the button is null
